<DOC><DOCNO> AP881008-0045 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0617EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Hostage'sSister     10-08 0311</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Hostage's Sister,0318</SECOND><HEAD>Sister Hopeful Anderson Will Be Released By Election</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Hostages</HEAD><BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The sister of the longest-held hostage inLebanon, journalist Terry Anderson, said it will be ``verydevastating'' to her brother if he is not released by the Nov. 8presidential election.   ``Terry is geared to the elections,'' Peggy Say said Friday,based on the word she received from a recently freed hostage.   ``He feels it will take that to get him out of there. I'm afraidif they come and go, it's going to be very devastating to him.''   The last word on Anderson's condition came from Marcel Fontaine,a French hostage released in May, said Mrs. Say, who lives inCadiz, Ky. Fontaine said Anderson was hanging on, with hopes ofrelease by the election.   A Beirut magazine said Friday the American hostages would befreed before the election. And an Israeli newspaper said the UnitedStates made a deal with Iran to free the American hostages inexchange for delivery of arms and spare parts to Iran through SouthKorea. U.S. officials denied the report.   Mrs. Say also criticized the U.S. government for refusing tonegotiate the release of her brother and the six other Americansheld by Islamic extremists in Lebanon.   Mrs. Say told editors and publishers Friday at the fallnewspaper meeting of the Kentucky Associated Press that the UnitedStates routinely has negotiated the release of other Americanhostages in the Middle East and elsewhere.   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The AssociatedPress, was abducted March 16, 1985. He will be 41 on Oct. 27.   Mithileshwar Singh, a 60-year-old Indian citizen and residentalien of the United States, was released Monday, raising hope forthe freedom of the other hostages. Mrs. Say said Singh was never incontact with her brother.</TEXT></DOC>